---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <BaseHead title="Design Choices, WLKOM" description="Technical justifications, design decisions, and failed attempts for the WLKOM rootkit project." />
</head>
<body>
  <Header />
  <main>

    <div class="page-header">
      <div class="badge">Technical rationale</div>
      <h1>// Design Choices & Failed Attempts</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Every non-obvious decision we made, why we made it, and what we tried before landing on the final approach.</p>
    </div>

    <nav class="toc">
      <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#rootkit-type">Rootkit type: LKM vs alternatives</a></li>
        <li><a href="#kernel-version">Kernel version choice</a></li>
        <li><a href="#distro">Distro choice</a></li>
        <li><a href="#c2-tech">C2 technology</a></li>
        <li><a href="#protocol">Communication protocol</a></li>
        <li><a href="#exec-design">Command execution design</a></li>
        <li><a href="#syscall-hook">Syscall hooking approach</a></li>
        <li><a href="#upload-design">Upload/Download design</a></li>
        <li><a href="#security-disabled">Security features disabled</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <!-- 1. Rootkit type -->
    <section class="section" id="rootkit-type">
      <h2 class="section-title">01 : Rootkit type: LKM vs alternatives</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">
        Three main categories of Linux rootkits exist. We had to pick one.
      </p>

      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Rejected</span>
            <strong>LD_PRELOAD userland hook</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Intercepts libc calls (open, read, getdents64…) by injecting a shared library via the <code>LD_PRELOAD</code> environment variable.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Only affects processes started with the env var set</li>
            <li>Does not affect processes that bypass libc (direct syscalls)</li>
            <li>Trivially detected: <code>env | grep LD_PRELOAD</code></li>
            <li>Does not survive reboots naturally</li>
            <li>No kernel-level visibility</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Rejected</span>
            <strong>eBPF rootkit</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Attaches eBPF programs to kernel tracepoints or kprobes to intercept and modify kernel behavior without a loadable module.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Requires kernel ≥ 5.7 with BTF and CO-RE support</li>
            <li>Requires the <code>CAP_BPF</code> / <code>CAP_SYS_ADMIN</code> capability</li>
            <li>eBPF verifier actively limits what programs can do (no arbitrary memory writes)</li>
            <li>Excellent for monitoring but limited for active rootkit operations</li>
            <li>More modern approach, interesting but beyond our scope</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card chosen">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag chosen-tag">Chosen</span>
            <strong>Linux Kernel Module (LKM)</strong>
          </div>
          <p>A <code>.ko</code> file loaded with <code>insmod</code> that runs in ring 0, the same privilege level as the kernel itself.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Full access to all kernel data structures and symbols</li>
            <li>Can hook syscalls by patching the syscall table directly</li>
            <li>Can spawn kernel threads, open network sockets, manipulate the VFS</li>
            <li>Can remove itself from the module list to hide from <code>lsmod</code></li>
            <li>Well-documented, extensive resources for learning kernel development</li>
            <li>Perfectly suited to a pedagogical project where understanding the kernel is the goal</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout">
        <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
        <p>An LKM rootkit is detectable if the defender knows where to look (memory scanning, integrity checking of the syscall table). For a pedagogical project this is a feature, not a bug, it forces us to implement real hiding techniques to understand how they work.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 2. Kernel version -->
    <section class="section" id="kernel-version">
      <h2 class="section-title">02 : Kernel version choice (6.6 LTS)</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">
        The subject asks us to justify technically why we cannot use a more recent kernel. Here is the honest answer.
      </p>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Our <strong>hide files</strong> and <strong>hide lines</strong> features rely on two low-level kernel techniques
          that have become progressively harder to use on recent kernels:
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="issue-list">
        <div class="issue">
          <div class="issue-title">Issue 1 : <code>kallsyms_lookup_name()</code> unexported (kernel ≥ 5.7)</div>
          <div class="issue-body">
            <p>
              Finding the address of the syscall table requires resolving the symbol
              <code>sys_call_table</code>, which is not exported. The canonical approach is to call
              <code>kallsyms_lookup_name()</code>, but this function was <strong>removed from the exported
              symbol set</strong> in kernel 5.7 (commit <code>0bd476f</code>).
            </p>
            <p>
              Our workaround: we use a <strong>kprobes trick</strong>, register a kprobe on
              <code>kallsyms_lookup_name</code> to recover its address, then call it directly via
              the recovered pointer. This works up to and including 6.6 LTS.
            </p>
            <p>
              On kernel ≥ 6.7, the kprobes approach itself may require additional permissions
              depending on the lockdown mode configuration.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="issue">
          <div class="issue-title">Issue 2 : CR0 Write-Protect trick and Intel CET/IBT (kernel ≥ 6.3)</div>
          <div class="issue-body">
            <p>
              Writing to the syscall table requires disabling the CPU's Write-Protect (WP) bit in
              register CR0, patching the pointer, then restoring WP. This is the standard trick.
            </p>
            <p>
              Starting with kernel 6.3 on CPUs with <strong>Intel Control-flow Enforcement Technology (CET)</strong>
              and Indirect Branch Tracking (IBT) enabled, <code>write_cr0()</code> is intercepted by the kernel's
              own CET enforcement. Calling it to clear the WP bit will trigger a fault on affected hardware.
            </p>
            <p>
              On 6.6 LTS with the school's hardware (which predates CET widespread adoption), this still
              works. On a machine with a Tiger Lake or newer Intel CPU and IBT enabled in the kernel config,
              this would fault.
            </p>
            <p>
              The correct modern approach would be to use <strong>ftrace-based function hooking</strong>
              or <strong>kprobe trampoline</strong> instead of direct table patching, both are compatible
              with recent kernels but significantly more complex to implement.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="issue">
          <div class="issue-title">Issue 3 : Kernel lockdown mode</div>
          <div class="issue-body">
            <p>
              Linux 5.4 introduced the <strong>Kernel Lockdown LSM</strong>. When active in integrity or
              confidentiality mode, it blocks: loading unsigned modules, direct
              memory access via <code>/dev/mem</code>, and access to <code>/proc/kallsyms</code> (in
              confidentiality mode).
            </p>
            <p>
              Arch Linux does <strong>not</strong> enable lockdown by default, so this is a non-issue on
              our target. However, on a distribution like Ubuntu 22.04 with Secure Boot, lockdown would
              be active and our module would not load.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict">
        <strong>Verdict:</strong> We target <strong>Linux 6.6 LTS</strong> because it is the most recent
        Long-Term Support kernel on which all our techniques (kprobes kallsyms resolution + CR0 WP trick)
        work reliably on the school's hardware without additional configuration. It also receives backported
        security patches until December 2026, making it a reasonable production-grade choice.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 3. Distro -->
    <section class="section" id="distro">
      <h2 class="section-title">03 : Distro choice (Arch Linux)</h2>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The subject allows any Linux distribution. We chose Arch Linux for both the host and the victim VM.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="reasons">
        <div class="reason">
          <span class="reason-num">01</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Exact kernel headers always available</strong>
            <p>Arch is a rolling release. The <code>linux-headers</code> package always matches the running <code>linux</code> kernel exactly. On distributions with fixed release cycles (Debian, Ubuntu), the headers package may lag behind the installed kernel, causing out-of-tree module build failures.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reason">
          <span class="reason-num">02</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Reproducible installation via <code>archinstall</code></strong>
            <p>The <code>archinstall</code> scripted installer accepts a JSON configuration file. This lets us version-control the entire VM setup: packages, bootloader, SSH config, fstab. Anyone can reproduce our VM in under 5 minutes.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reason">
          <span class="reason-num">03</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Minimal base install</strong>
            <p>An Arch base install is ~800 MB. There are no services running by default beyond what we explicitly install, SSH, getty. This makes it easier to reason about what's running on the victim and keeps the environment clean for testing.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reason">
          <span class="reason-num">04</span>
          <div>
            <strong>School standard</strong>
            <p>The school's laptops run Arch Linux. Using the same distribution for the victim VM means the kernel version matches the host when compiling the module natively, and our teammates are already familiar with <code>pacman</code>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reason">
          <span class="reason-num">05</span>
          <div>
            <strong>No mandatory security framework</strong>
            <p>Arch doesn't ship SELinux or AppArmor by default. We don't need to write policy rules to allow our module to operate. This is intentional for a pedagogical project, one fewer variable to debug.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 4. C2 technology -->
    <section class="section" id="c2-tech">
      <h2 class="section-title">04 : C2 server: Flask/Python</h2>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The subject is technology-agnostic for the attacking program. We chose Python with Flask.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Considered</span>
            <strong>C + raw sockets</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Writing the C2 in C would be consistent with the rootkit side. However, building a web UI and SQLite persistence in C adds significant boilerplate with no educational benefit. The rootkit itself already gives us plenty of C to write.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Considered</span>
            <strong>Go / Node.js</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Both have good HTTP frameworks and are fast to develop with. We ruled them out because the team already knows Python and Flask, and the project's tight deadline made familiarity more valuable than language performance.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card chosen">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag chosen-tag">Chosen</span>
            <strong>Python + Flask</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Flask gives us routing, Jinja2 templating, and session management in under 200 lines. SQLite3 is in the standard library. The result is a full web UI with per-machine history, AJAX live updates, and file transfer, with minimal code complexity.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 5. Protocol -->
    <section class="section" id="protocol">
      <h2 class="section-title">05 : Communication protocol: HTTP/1.0 polling</h2>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Choosing how the rootkit communicates with the C2 was one of the most consequential
          architectural decisions, because the kernel networking API is significantly more
          constrained than userland.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Rejected</span>
            <strong>Persistent TCP socket (push model)</strong>
          </div>
          <p>The C2 keeps a persistent TCP connection open and pushes commands as they arrive. This eliminates polling latency.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Requires implementing a framing protocol (length-prefixed messages or line-delimited)</li>
            <li>Must handle connection drops and reconnects in the kernel polling thread</li>
            <li>Select/epoll are not available in kernel space, blocking I/O only</li>
            <li>Much harder to implement correctly from a kernel thread with <code>kernel_recvmsg()</code></li>
          </ul>
          <p class="attempt-note">We attempted this first (see Failed Attempts section). The reconnect logic became complex enough that we pivoted.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card chosen">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag chosen-tag">Chosen</span>
            <strong>HTTP/1.0 short polling</strong>
          </div>
          <p>The rootkit opens a new TCP connection for each request, sends an HTTP/1.0 request, reads the response, and closes the connection. A kernel thread repeats this every 5 seconds.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Stateless, no connection state to manage across polls</li>
            <li>HTTP/1.0 (no keep-alive) means the server closes the connection after the response, so we know exactly when reading is done</li>
            <li>If the C2 is unreachable, the connect fails and we simply retry next cycle</li>
            <li>HTTP is firewall-friendly (port 5000, looks like web traffic)</li>
            <li>Tradeoff: up to 5 seconds of command latency</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout">
        <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
        <p><strong>Why HTTP/1.0 specifically and not HTTP/1.1?</strong> HTTP/1.1 defaults to keep-alive (persistent connections) and may use chunked transfer encoding. Both require more parsing logic. HTTP/1.0 is simple: send headers, read until the server closes. A single <code>kernel_recvmsg()</code> loop suffices.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 6. Exec design -->
    <section class="section" id="exec-design">
      <h2 class="section-title">06 : Command execution: temp files for output capture</h2>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Executing a command from kernel space and capturing its output is non-trivial.
          Kernel threads have no file descriptors, no terminal, and no stdin/stdout.
          We considered several approaches.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Rejected</span>
            <strong>Pipes via kernel_pipe()</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Create a pipe, pass the write end as stdout for the child process, read from the read end in the kernel thread.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><code>kernel_pipe()</code> is not a public kernel API</li>
            <li>Passing a pipe fd to <code>call_usermodehelper</code>'s subprocess requires modifying the subprocess's file descriptor table before exec, not straightforward with the UMH API</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Rejected</span>
            <strong>Shared memory / tmpfs</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Map a shared memory region, have the child write to it.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Child process needs to know the address, requires injecting extra setup code</li>
            <li>More complex to synchronize (how do we know the child is done writing?)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card chosen">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag chosen-tag">Chosen</span>
            <strong>Temp files in <code>/rootkit/</code></strong>
          </div>
          <p>Wrap the command: <code>cmd &gt;/rootkit/stdout 2&gt;/rootkit/stderr; echo $? &gt;/rootkit/exitcode</code>. After <code>UMH_WAIT_PROC</code> returns, read the three files with our kernel VFS helpers.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Shell handles the redirection natively, zero kernel-side complexity</li>
            <li><code>read_file()</code> is a simple VFS wrapper we already have</li>
            <li><code>UMH_WAIT_PROC</code> blocks until <code>/bin/sh</code> exits, so files are fully written before we read</li>
            <li>Tradeoff: writes to disk (minor), but the files are in <code>/rootkit/</code> which is hidden from userland</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 7. Syscall hooking -->
    <section class="section" id="syscall-hook">
      <h2 class="section-title">07 : Syscall hooking: CR0 WP bit</h2>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          To hook <code>getdents64</code> and <code>read()</code>, we need to write a new function pointer
          into the syscall table, a read-only memory page by default.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Considered</span>
            <strong>ftrace-based hooking</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Use the kernel's built-in function tracing infrastructure to intercept function calls without patching memory directly.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Works on all modern kernels including ≥ 6.6</li>
            <li>No need to find the syscall table address</li>
            <li>More complex API (<code>ftrace_ops</code>, <code>FTRACE_OPS_FL_SAVE_REGS</code>…)</li>
            <li>Requires the kernel to be compiled with <code>CONFIG_FUNCTION_TRACER=y</code> (not guaranteed)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Considered</span>
            <strong>kprobe on syscall handler</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Attach a kprobe to the syscall entry point to intercept calls before they reach the real handler.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Clean API, widely documented</li>
            <li>Can only inspect registers and memory, not easily modify return values mid-flight</li>
            <li>Adding a kretprobe to modify the result is possible but adds complexity</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card chosen">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag chosen-tag">Chosen</span>
            <strong>Direct syscall table patching (CR0 WP bit)</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Find the syscall table via kprobes-resolved <code>kallsyms_lookup_name</code>. Disable WP in CR0, overwrite the function pointer, restore WP.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Simplest to understand, directly maps to "replace function pointer"</li>
            <li>Works cleanly on kernel 6.6 LTS on our hardware</li>
            <li>Well documented in rootkit literature, educational value is high</li>
            <li>Limitation: doesn't work on CPUs with Intel CET/IBT on kernels ≥ 6.3 (see kernel version section)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 8. Upload/Download -->
    <section class="section" id="upload-design">
      <h2 class="section-title">08 : Upload/Download: URL-safe base64 path encoding</h2>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          File paths like <code>/etc/shadow</code> contain slashes and special characters that break
          URL routing. We needed a way to embed an arbitrary file path in a URL segment.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Rejected</span>
            <strong>URL percent-encoding</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Encode <code>/</code> as <code>%2F</code>, spaces as <code>%20</code>, etc.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Flask (and most HTTP frameworks) automatically decode <code>%2F</code> back to <code>/</code> before routing, causing path confusion</li>
            <li>The slash issue requires special Flask config (<code>strict_slashes=False</code>, custom converters) and is fragile</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card rejected">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag rejected-tag">Rejected</span>
            <strong>POST body for the path</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Send the path in the POST body instead of the URL.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Works for the download request, but the kernel-side HTTP client would need to parse a JSON or form body to get the path</li>
            <li>Adds parsing complexity in the kernel where we want to keep things simple</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="comp-card chosen">
          <div class="comp-header">
            <span class="comp-tag chosen-tag">Chosen</span>
            <strong>URL-safe base64 (no padding)</strong>
          </div>
          <p>Encode the path as URL-safe base64 (RFC 4648 §5): <code>+</code>→<code>-</code>, <code>/</code>→<code>_</code>, no <code>=</code> padding. The encoded string contains only alphanumerics, <code>-</code>, and <code>_</code>, all safe in a URL path segment.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Example: <code>/etc/shadow</code> → <code>L2V0Yy9zaGFkb3c</code></li>
            <li>Implemented in kernel with a custom <code>b64url_encode()</code> (no external deps)</li>
            <li>Flask decodes with <code>base64.urlsafe_b64decode(path_b64 + '==')</code></li>
            <li>Clean, reversible, no parsing ambiguity</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout">
        <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
        <p><strong>Binary file transfers:</strong> A second challenge was sending binary file content over HTTP from the kernel. <code>strlen()</code> stops at the first null byte, making it useless for binary payloads. We pass an explicit <code>body_len</code> parameter to our HTTP POST helper and use <code>memcpy</code> instead of string functions everywhere in the HTTP body construction.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 9. Security features disabled -->
    <section class="section" id="security-disabled">
      <h2 class="section-title">09 : Security features disabled on the victim</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">
        The subject asks us to document every security feature we disable and explain why technically.
      </p>

      <div class="issue-list">
        <div class="issue">
          <div class="issue-title">SSH PermitRootLogin yes</div>
          <div class="issue-body">
            <p>
              Default Arch SSH config sets <code>PermitRootLogin prohibit-password</code>.
              We change it to <code>yes</code> to allow password-based root login for easy access to the VM.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>Technical justification:</strong> This is a pedagogical project. We deploy via the shared
              virtio-9p folder and SSH for interactive work. In a real deployment, root login over SSH would be
              disabled in favour of a non-root user with <code>sudo</code>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="issue">
          <div class="issue-title">No Secure Boot / no module signing</div>
          <div class="issue-body">
            <p>
              Our <code>wlkom.ko</code> is not signed. Loading an unsigned module requires either
              Secure Boot to be disabled or the kernel to be compiled without
              <code>CONFIG_MODULE_SIG_FORCE=y</code>.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>Technical justification:</strong> Signing a kernel module requires either a key enrolled
              in the UEFI MOK database (complex to automate in a VM) or compiling the module with the kernel's
              own build key. Since we use a stock Arch kernel, module signing is set to
              <code>CONFIG_MODULE_SIG=n</code>, unsigned modules are permitted by default. We leave this as-is.
              In a real scenario, a rootkit would likely exploit a vulnerability to load without signing.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="issue">
          <div class="issue-title">SELinux / AppArmor : not installed</div>
          <div class="issue-body">
            <p>
              The stock Arch Linux kernel is compiled without mandatory access control frameworks active
              by default. Neither SELinux nor AppArmor is installed in our base configuration.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>Technical justification:</strong> SELinux would need a policy that allows our module to
              make network connections from kernel context, write to <code>/rootkit/</code>, and hook syscalls.
              Writing such a policy is outside the scope of this project. We intentionally keep the victim
              minimal so the rootkit behaviour is the only variable.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="issue">
          <div class="issue-title">SMEP / SMAP : left enabled</div>
          <div class="issue-body">
            <p>
              Supervisor Mode Execution Prevention (SMEP) and Supervisor Mode Access Prevention (SMAP)
              are <strong>left enabled</strong>. They prevent kernel code from executing in userland pages
              and from accessing userland memory without explicit <code>copy_from_user</code> /
              <code>copy_to_user</code> wrappers.
            </p>
            <p>
              Our rootkit does not need to disable them: we don't execute userland pages from ring 0,
              and we use the proper VFS / usermodehelper APIs. Disabling SMEP/SMAP would be a red flag
              and is unnecessary.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>


  </main>
  <Footer />
</body>
</html>

